vectorData.altText: an intervertebral disc can herniate     , such that the nucleus pulposus pushes through the annulus fibrosis into the intervertebral foramen, thus compressing a spinal nerve or its root.

Each vertebral body is joined to the next by an intervertebral disc, which consists of an outer, tough, fibrocartilaginous annulus fibrosus     , and a gelatinous core called the nucleus pulposus     . The intervertebral disc offers tough, flexible support; the highly hydrated nucleus pulposis withstands compression and is very deformable, thereby permitting flexion     , extension      and rotation     of the vertebral column.
rotation occurs around the long axis of a body part; you rotate your vertebral column when you turn to the right and the left
extension increases the angle between articulating elements; you extend your vertebral column when you stand up straight
flexion decreases the angle between articulating elements; you flex your vertebral column when you bend forward
protrusion of a structure or substance through the tissues that normally contain it
